Gross description:  The first specimen is received in formalin and labeled with the patient's full name and full social security number, and additionally labeled "right posterior lateral bladder tumors", and consists of multiple tan-brown issue fragments measuring 3.1 x 2.1 x 0.4 cm that are entirely submitted in cassettes A1 and A2.           The second specimen is received in formalin and labeled with the patient's full name and full social security number, and additionally labeled "trigonal erythema", and consists of one tissue fragment measuring 0.3 x 0.3 x 0.3 cm that is inked blue and bisected before being entirely submitted in cassette B.    Microscopic exam/diagnosis:  COMMENT: Histologic sections of the right posterior lateral tumor (part A) shows papillary urothelial carcinoma with several foci showing features of high-grade papillary urothelial carcinoma in a background oflow-grade papillary urothelial carcinoma. Sections of the trigonalerythema (B) show benign urothelial mucosa with reactive changes andmixed inflammation in the lamina propria. There is no evidence of carcinoma. Multiple step-leveled sections were examined for part B. tumor_notes: 2.5 cm papillary tumor that was covering the right ureteral orifice.  The left ureteral orifice was normal apperaing and hed efflux of urine.  There were some small papillary tumor carpeting surrounding the main bladder tumor, around a 2cm area close towards the bladder neck.

FINDINGS:   About 1cm of low-lying papillary lesion identified on right lateral wall which   was biopsied/fulgurated, and 2mm area of early-appearing papillary tumor   fulgurated on left posterior wall.  Comment:  Multiple step-leveled sections have been examined.        Histologic sections show scant papillary-like structures lined by        atypical cells with a disorderly appearance, mild to moderate nuclear        pleomorphism and nuclear enlargement. The findings are focal but favor        the diagnosis of high-grade non-invasive papillary urothelial        carcinoma. There is no in situ carcinoma. A small amount of smooth        muscle is identified, but definitive muscularis propria is not        present.
